         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(the one who in morality, energy, meditation and) knowledge surpasses (all beings), he who with the 32 marks and the 80 ornaments and the insatiably to-look-at, Buddha-like</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>23</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>25</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2010"/><citedRange>171</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>100</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">body is adorned and decorated. If he had not left the house, he would have become a ruler over the four continents,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>32</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>44</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970a"/><citedRange>467</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1976"/><citedRange>228</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3 #a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If he had not left the house, he would have become a cakravartin king, endowed with the seven jewels, a ruler over the four continents, and I too, and you too, we would have become his servants.  (cf 25)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>272</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">a cakravartin king, endowed with the seven jewels, and I too, and you too, we would have become his servants.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">He now [however,] has left the house, truly knowing all Dharmas together, (making ) all doubts</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4 #a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>139</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>167</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(disappear), giving all the questions an end. This now, the Arhat’s Buddha-</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5 #a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>92</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Den bu(ddhaschaftlichen Körper) des Arhat quält jetzt, wenn er (seines Weges) geht, Erkrankung durch den Wind.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Illness because of the wind now torments the Bu(ddha-like body) of the arhat, when he goes (on his way).</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>497</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1966"/><citedRange>265</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">like body, in going (his way), is tormented by disease from the wind. Therefore he requires warm water and oil of sesame</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>190</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>201</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2012"/><citedRange>64</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... || In the K.-tune: || Like to a son the Buddha, the master sent me to you with a plea. You, however, (accompany?) me to</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>319</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>487</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the Buddha. Bring oil and warm water yourself, and look at the teacher with your own eyes. Your eyes will be successful</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Bringe selbst Öl [und] warmes Wasser, sieh mit eigenen Augen den Meister!</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Yourself, bring oil [and] warm water, see the master with [your] own eyes!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>190, 399</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2 #b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>190</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Bring oil and warm water yourself, and look at the teacher with your own eyes. Your eyes will be successful [and] your human birth will be successful.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>228</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[and] your human birth will be successful. 1. Surprised Bṛhaddyuti, the potter, thinks: Oh</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">O so wonderful is mere human birth, if it is endowed with such virtue!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>283</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">how much amazing (is) the mere human birth, if it is endowed with such virtue! Thereupon Bṛhaddyuti,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4 txt:m-a22#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>99f</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970"/><citedRange>279</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>431</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1976a"/><citedRange>72</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979d"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the potter, together with [his] father, mother and brothers, with [his] wife and children, after having (gathered) perfume, flower[s], warm water and oil of sesame</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>79</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>23</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">went to where Śākyamuni, the Buddha, the god of gods was. [And] there he saw, Śākyamuni, the Buddha, the (god) of gods</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6 txt:m-a22#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
